A few years agoI was looking at a suit of armor with
the hinged cutout on the chest piece. It was made to
open to the right instead of left. The owner said it
was made for a left handed samurai. He said before
Tokugawa era there were the standard amount of left
handed samurai as any population but that after Edo
started they were forced to change. FWIW BOb Elder
--- Gordon Robson &lt;robsongo@...&gt; wrote:

&gt; 
&gt; Hi John,
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; If you refer to the Tokyo National Museum&#39;s
&gt; publication on Uchigatana
&gt; Koshirae, you will note several Tensho period mounts
&gt; arranged for wear on
&gt; the right side. There is some question as to whether
&gt; or not they were for
&gt; wear with the cutting edge down. I don&#39;t know of any
&gt; illustrations showing
&gt; right handed wear. I might add that to the best of
&gt; my knowledge there is no
&gt; such thing as an entirely left-handed person.
&gt; Left-handed individuals either
&gt; due to nurture or nature seem to do some things with
&gt; the right-hand and
&gt; others with the left and sometimes able to use both
&gt; for the same thing.
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; Gordon
